00:02:03.490 --> 00:02:05.050
from the way it really is.

00:02:05.050 --> 00:02:06.970
So if you believe
in illusions, you

00:02:06.970 --> 00:02:09.490
think that you actually evolve
to see the world accurately.

00:02:09.490 --> 00:02:13.040
Most of the time, it's just
that sometimes you get it wrong.

00:02:13.040 --> 00:02:14.860
So what we can do
is do a quick test

00:02:14.860 --> 00:02:17.151
to see how good you are at
seeing the world accurately.

00:02:17.151 --> 00:02:20.120
So how many bears do you see?

00:02:20.120 --> 00:02:23.180
Three-- only three?

00:02:23.180 --> 00:02:25.170
Did you see-- oh,
you only saw two?

00:02:25.170 --> 00:02:27.120
OK, keep looking around.

00:02:27.120 --> 00:02:28.643
Look differently.

00:02:31.960 --> 00:02:32.770
Turn your head.

00:02:32.770 --> 00:02:35.040
Imagine.

00:02:35.040 --> 00:02:36.565
Can you see four?

00:02:36.565 --> 00:02:37.870
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] five.

00:02:37.870 --> 00:02:39.160
BEAU LOTTO: Five, six.

00:02:39.160 --> 00:02:41.140
Do I hear six?

00:02:41.140 --> 00:02:42.454
It's like an auction.

00:02:42.454 --> 00:02:43.679
AUDIENCE: Is there a panda?

00:02:43.679 --> 00:02:45.845
BEAU LOTTO: You see a--
yeah, there could be pandas.

00:02:45.845 --> 00:02:48.130
It's a bear, right?

00:02:48.130 --> 00:02:50.420
There are 11 bears hiding there.

00:02:50.420 --> 00:02:51.587
Right?

00:02:51.587 --> 00:02:53.170
The point is, the
more differently you

00:02:53.170 --> 00:02:54.919
look at something, the
more things reveal.

00:02:54.919 --> 00:02:57.430
But that's actually
quite a complex scene,

00:02:57.430 --> 00:02:59.830
so we could try something
much simpler, which

00:02:59.830 --> 00:03:01.364
is much more natural.

00:03:01.364 --> 00:03:03.280
So how many of you can
see the predator that's

00:03:03.280 --> 00:03:04.720
about to jump out at you?

00:03:04.720 --> 00:03:07.600
And if you haven't seen it
yet, you're dead, right?

00:03:07.600 --> 00:03:08.932
Especially here.

00:03:08.932 --> 00:03:10.780
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:10.780 --> 00:03:13.510
So who thinks they can
save the rest of the room?

00:03:13.510 --> 00:03:15.631
Where do you think it is?

00:03:15.631 --> 00:03:17.460
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:03:17.460 --> 00:03:19.180
BEAU LOTTO: Right-- up there?

00:03:19.180 --> 00:03:19.750
At the top?

00:03:19.750 --> 00:03:20.924
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:03:20.924 --> 00:03:22.090
BEAU LOTTO: OK, you're dead.

00:03:22.090 --> 00:03:23.955
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:23.955 --> 00:03:25.600
OK.

00:03:25.600 --> 00:03:27.697
OK, let's just add 10%
of the information,

00:03:27.697 --> 00:03:30.280
because 90% of the information
your brain uses to see actually

00:03:30.280 --> 00:03:31.870
comes from grayscale.

00:03:31.870 --> 00:03:34.090
So we'll add 10%
to the information.

00:03:34.090 --> 00:03:35.750
And can you find it now?

00:03:35.750 --> 00:03:36.250
All right.

00:03:36.250 --> 00:03:38.500
For those who maybe shouldn't
be Google, there it is.

00:03:38.500 --> 00:03:39.580
OK.

00:03:39.580 --> 00:03:43.430
So now we go back, you can see,
it was always staring at you.

00:03:43.430 --> 00:03:44.976
It was always there.

00:03:44.976 --> 00:03:46.600
And this makes a
really important point

00:03:46.600 --> 00:03:50.170
when it comes to vision,
which is only 10%

00:03:50.170 --> 00:03:51.400
of the information--

00:03:51.400 --> 00:03:52.570
you can come on in--

00:03:52.570 --> 00:03:54.190
which is only 10%
of the information

00:03:54.190 --> 00:03:58.600
your brain uses to see
actually comes from your eyes.

00:03:58.600 --> 00:04:02.500
The other 90% comes from
other parts of your brain.

00:04:02.500 --> 00:04:04.330
So your eyes are
almost pointless when

00:04:04.330 --> 00:04:06.250
it comes to vision, right?

00:04:06.250 --> 00:04:08.270
It's like the keyboard
is to a computer.

00:04:08.270 --> 00:04:09.894
It's how you get the
stuff in, but it's

00:04:09.894 --> 00:04:12.460
very little to that
you actually see.

00:04:12.460 --> 00:04:14.980
But again, this is still
a fairly complex scene.

00:04:14.980 --> 00:04:17.740
So let's try something
even simpler,

00:04:17.740 --> 00:04:19.180
which is just lightness.

00:04:19.180 --> 00:04:22.540
Surely people at Google
can see the world

00:04:22.540 --> 00:04:25.330
accurately in terms of
light intensity, right?

00:04:25.330 --> 00:04:26.920
Even jellyfish
can see lightness,

00:04:26.920 --> 00:04:28.960
and they don't even
have a brain, right?

00:04:28.960 --> 00:04:31.720
So surely, you can see
the world accurately.

00:04:31.720 --> 00:04:34.044
And if that's true, then
things that are the same

00:04:34.044 --> 00:04:36.460
should always look the same,
and things that are different

00:04:36.460 --> 00:04:37.994
should always look different.

00:04:37.994 --> 00:04:39.910
And these two circles
are physically the same.

00:04:39.910 --> 00:04:41.830
And do they look the same?

00:04:41.830 --> 00:04:42.360
Yeah?

00:04:42.360 --> 00:04:42.859
Right?

00:04:42.859 --> 00:04:45.700
So thank goodness, at
least at this level,

00:04:45.700 --> 00:04:47.830
you can see the
world accurately.

00:04:47.830 --> 00:04:51.580
But what happens if I
don't change those dots,

00:04:51.580 --> 00:04:54.760
I just change what
surrounds them?

00:04:54.760 --> 00:04:56.950
What happens to your perception?

00:04:56.950 --> 00:04:59.109
Do they still look the same?

00:04:59.109 --> 00:04:59.650
AUDIENCE: No.

00:04:59.650 --> 00:05:00.190
BEAU LOTTO: No.

00:05:00.190 --> 00:05:02.106
The one on the left will
probably look lighter

00:05:02.106 --> 00:05:04.680
than the one on the right, yes?

00:05:04.680 --> 00:05:06.030
And this makes it--

00:05:06.030 --> 00:05:08.640
so nothing's actually changing
on those circles, just

00:05:08.640 --> 00:05:10.590
your perception of them.

00:05:10.590 --> 00:05:12.930
And this is the simplest
illusion that your brain has,

00:05:12.930 --> 00:05:14.971
which is called simultaneous
brightness contrast,

00:05:14.971 --> 00:05:17.200
and we really don't
know how it works.

00:05:17.200 --> 00:05:20.470
But what it demonstrates is
the most basic level of vision,

00:05:20.470 --> 00:05:22.740
of perception, which remember,
underpins everything it

00:05:22.740 --> 00:05:26.130
is to be you, context
is everything.

00:05:26.130 --> 00:05:29.910
Your brain did not actually
evolve to do absolutes.

00:05:29.910 --> 00:05:32.050
It evolved to do relationships.

00:05:32.050 --> 00:05:37.380
It's not interested unless it's
contextual in contrast, OK?

00:05:37.380 --> 00:05:41.190
So much so that as you're
looking at me right now,

00:05:41.190 --> 00:05:42.810
your eyes are actually moving.

00:05:42.810 --> 00:05:45.210
They're called saccades
and microsaccades.

00:05:45.210 --> 00:05:48.690
And you can stop your eyes
from moving by closing one eye,

00:05:48.690 --> 00:05:52.000
sticking your finger into the
tear duct, and pushing back--

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:52.500
right?

00:05:52.500 --> 00:05:55.180
You can do it at home with your
kids or your friends, right?

00:05:55.180 --> 00:05:57.990
And you're basically
pushing your eyeball back

00:05:57.990 --> 00:06:01.620
into its socket, and
your eye stops moving.

00:06:01.620 --> 00:06:03.360
What happens?

00:06:03.360 --> 00:06:06.000
Your eyes open, and your
eyeballs stop moving.

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:08.090
What do you think happened?

00:06:08.090 --> 00:06:09.065
You go blind.

00:06:09.065 --> 00:06:11.190
Of course, you'll go blind
if you shove your finger

00:06:11.190 --> 00:06:12.180
into the back, right?

00:06:12.180 --> 00:06:14.790
But by just simply stopping
your eye from moving,

00:06:14.790 --> 00:06:17.190
your brain has nothing
interesting to see,

00:06:17.190 --> 00:06:21.280
because it's only interested
in change in space and time.

00:06:21.280 --> 00:06:25.890
So if you stop change,
your brain goes blind, OK?

00:06:25.890 --> 00:06:31.200
So we've known that
context is everything

00:06:31.200 --> 00:06:34.320
for a very long time,
but a far deeper question

00:06:34.320 --> 00:06:37.320
is not that context is
everything, but why it is.

00:06:37.320 --> 00:06:39.624
And to understand why
context is everything

00:06:39.624 --> 00:06:41.040
is really to
understand what it is

00:06:41.040 --> 00:06:43.290
to be human, but also to
understand how it is we can

00:06:43.290 --> 00:06:46.140
help people to see differently.

00:06:46.140 --> 00:06:49.410
So instead of telling you,
I'm going to show you.

00:06:49.410 --> 00:06:53.280
And this is actually at the
heart of machine vision,

00:06:53.280 --> 00:06:56.740
of automatic cars, et cetera.

00:06:56.740 --> 00:06:59.100
This is the fundamental
problem that visual systems

00:06:59.100 --> 00:06:59.850
evolved to solve.

00:06:59.850 --> 00:07:02.490
So hold up your
finger, and see if you

00:07:02.490 --> 00:07:05.340
can make your finger the
same size as me by lining up

00:07:05.340 --> 00:07:06.960
your finger with me, right?

00:07:06.960 --> 00:07:09.390
The right finger, right?

00:07:09.390 --> 00:07:12.030
Can you make us the same size?

00:07:12.030 --> 00:07:12.910
Yes?

00:07:12.910 --> 00:07:13.410
OK.

00:07:13.410 --> 00:07:17.022
We're not the same size, right?

00:07:17.022 --> 00:07:17.730
This is because--

00:07:17.730 --> 00:07:19.080
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:19.080 --> 00:07:20.280
--right?

00:07:20.280 --> 00:07:22.680
But as far as your eye is
concerned, we are the same.

00:07:22.680 --> 00:07:25.950
It's because data that falls
onto your eyes, into your ears,

00:07:25.950 --> 00:07:28.960
onto your skin conflates
multiple aspects of the world.

00:07:28.960 --> 00:07:31.590
In this case, size
and distance, right?

00:07:31.590 --> 00:07:34.860
But the only access
we have to the world

00:07:34.860 --> 00:07:37.920
is the data that
your senses detect.

00:07:37.920 --> 00:07:39.990
But the data that
your senses detect

00:07:39.990 --> 00:07:43.680
is completely
meaningless, right?

00:07:43.680 --> 00:07:47.290
Which makes data itself-- so
who's working on big data?

00:07:47.290 --> 00:07:48.750
We're at Google, right?

00:07:48.750 --> 00:07:51.690
Data is pointless, right?

00:07:51.690 --> 00:07:53.760
It is literally pointless
in and of itself

00:07:53.760 --> 00:07:56.280
because it doesn't tell
your brain what to do.

00:07:56.280 --> 00:07:58.170
It doesn't come
with instructions.

00:07:58.170 --> 00:08:00.810
It conflates multiple
aspects of the world.

00:08:00.810 --> 00:08:03.360
And this is true at the
most fundamental level

00:08:03.360 --> 00:08:04.170
of perception.

00:08:04.170 --> 00:08:05.730
It could be a loud
thing far away

00:08:05.730 --> 00:08:09.150
or a quiet object up close, or a
bright object under dark light,

00:08:09.150 --> 00:08:11.971
or a dark object under
bright light, right?

00:08:11.971 --> 00:08:13.470
These different
aspects of the world

00:08:13.470 --> 00:08:17.730
can give rise to
identical pieces of data,

00:08:17.730 --> 00:08:21.430
but we have no
access to that world.

00:08:21.430 --> 00:08:26.670
So how does your brain deal
with the fundamental challenge

00:08:26.670 --> 00:08:29.010
that it is to survive,
which is uncertainty?

00:08:29.010 --> 00:08:31.990
This is the problem that
every single brain--

00:08:31.990 --> 00:08:34.740
in fact, every
single neural net--

00:08:34.740 --> 00:08:38.760
is adapted to deal with, which
is uncertainty, ambiguity.

00:08:38.760 --> 00:08:40.440
So what's the other
piece of information

00:08:40.440 --> 00:08:43.490
your brain has to see, except
for the data and the moment?

00:08:46.420 --> 00:08:47.960
What else does it
have access to?

00:08:47.960 --> 00:08:48.930
AUDIENCE: Memory.

00:08:48.930 --> 00:08:50.260
BEAU LOTTO: Memory.

00:08:50.260 --> 00:08:51.102
Experience.

00:08:51.102 --> 00:08:52.810
So the functional
structure of your brain

00:08:52.810 --> 00:08:54.520
is literally a
physical manifestation

00:08:54.520 --> 00:08:56.380
of its past interactions
with the world.

00:08:56.380 --> 00:09:00.100
And not a passive interaction,
but a physical interaction.

00:09:00.100 --> 00:09:02.860
Your brain makes meaning
by physically interacting

00:09:02.860 --> 00:09:05.950
with the sources of
the meaningless data,

00:09:05.950 --> 00:09:08.800
and it makes meaning from it.

00:09:08.800 --> 00:09:11.230
That's how your brain
then shapes itself.

00:09:11.230 --> 00:09:13.940
It's not a passive
receiving of information,

00:09:13.940 --> 00:09:16.270
which is why your brain
actually evolved to continually

00:09:16.270 --> 00:09:19.000
redefine normality, right?

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:21.220
And you see everything
relative to that

00:09:21.220 --> 00:09:23.355
continually changing normal.

00:09:23.355 --> 00:09:25.730
So I want to show you how
quickly your brain can redefine

00:09:25.730 --> 00:09:28.810
normality by first noticing
that those two desert scenes are

00:09:28.810 --> 00:09:30.310
basically the same, yes?

00:09:30.310 --> 00:09:31.976
One is just a flipping
of the other one.

00:09:31.976 --> 00:09:33.430
In terms of color, the same.

00:09:33.430 --> 00:09:36.970
I want you to stare at the dot
between the red and the green.

00:09:36.970 --> 00:09:38.846
Don't look anywhere else.

00:09:38.846 --> 00:09:40.720
OK, we're going to do
a bit of a magic trick,

00:09:40.720 --> 00:09:44.776
but it's going to happen
inside your head, OK?

00:09:44.776 --> 00:09:46.150
So as you're
staring at that dot,

00:09:46.150 --> 00:09:48.400
your brain is
redefining normality.

00:09:48.400 --> 00:09:51.070
It's learning that the left
side of its visual field

00:09:51.070 --> 00:09:53.500
is under green light and
the right side is under red.

00:09:53.500 --> 00:09:56.600
That's becoming its
new reality, right?

00:09:56.600 --> 00:09:58.819
You're also getting very sleepy.

00:09:58.819 --> 00:09:59.860
Keep looking at that dot.

00:09:59.860 --> 00:10:00.730
Don't look anywhere else.

00:10:00.730 --> 00:10:02.313
When I tell you to,
I want you to look

00:10:02.313 --> 00:10:04.914
at the dot between the
desert scenes, but not yet.

00:10:04.914 --> 00:10:10.570
OK, five, four, three, two, one.

00:10:10.570 --> 00:10:11.950
Do they still look the same?

00:10:11.950 --> 00:10:12.766
AUDIENCE: No.

00:10:12.766 --> 00:10:13.390
BEAU LOTTO: No?

00:10:13.390 --> 00:10:15.490
The one on the left should look
reddish, the one on the right

00:10:15.490 --> 00:10:16.750
should look greenish.

00:10:16.750 --> 00:10:17.920
Yes?

00:10:17.920 --> 00:10:19.540
And now as you look
around, your brain

00:10:19.540 --> 00:10:22.300
will continue to
redefine normality again.

00:10:22.300 --> 00:10:23.290
Yes?

00:10:23.290 --> 00:10:25.810
So that's how quick your
brain redefines normality

00:10:25.810 --> 00:10:28.450
at the most basic
level of lightness.

00:10:28.450 --> 00:10:31.360
So when you open your
eyes, what do you see?

00:10:31.360 --> 00:10:32.920
You can't see the
world as it really

00:10:32.920 --> 00:10:36.130
is because your brain is
forever separate from that.

00:10:36.130 --> 00:10:37.610
You can't see the
data, or it would

00:10:37.610 --> 00:10:41.150
be pointless to see the data,
because it could mean anything.

00:10:41.150 --> 00:10:44.030
So instead, what you
see is a meaning that

00:10:44.030 --> 00:10:46.220
was useful to see in the past.

00:10:46.220 --> 00:10:48.620
You see what we call the
empirical significance

00:10:48.620 --> 00:10:49.340
of information.

00:10:49.340 --> 00:10:52.400
You see the behavioral value
of the data, not the data.

00:10:52.400 --> 00:10:56.090
That is literally what
you're seeing, right?

00:10:56.090 --> 00:10:59.120
So the reason why
your brain adapts

00:10:59.120 --> 00:11:02.970
is because what was once
useful may no longer be useful.

00:11:02.970 --> 00:11:05.120
So your brain is continually
redefining normality

00:11:05.120 --> 00:11:07.947
and seeing things relative
to that changing normal.

00:11:07.947 --> 00:11:10.280
So to give you a sense of
what I mean by seeing meaning,

00:11:10.280 --> 00:11:11.904
we'll do it in the
context of language,

00:11:11.904 --> 00:11:13.910
so we'll pretend like
we're in a classroom, OK?

00:11:13.910 --> 00:11:16.910
So in the next few slides, I
want you to read what you see.

00:11:16.910 --> 00:11:18.920
We'll do it all together, OK?

