No.

00:13:17.870 --> 00:13:20.420
The red table is simply the
green table on its side.

00:13:20.420 --> 00:13:22.730
They have the exact
same dimensions.

00:13:22.730 --> 00:13:26.160
The only thing that varies
are the angles at the corner.

00:13:26.160 --> 00:13:29.557
Again, you're seeing the meaning
of the data, not the data.

00:13:29.557 --> 00:13:31.140
It would be pointless
to see the data.

00:13:31.140 --> 00:13:33.752
The data is they have the
exact same dimensions.

00:13:33.752 --> 00:13:35.320
But behaviorally,
that wouldn't have

00:13:35.320 --> 00:13:38.950
been useful in the
past, given the context.

00:13:38.950 --> 00:13:41.380
And what's true
for color and form

00:13:41.380 --> 00:13:44.080
is also true for more
complex perceptions,

00:13:44.080 --> 00:13:46.660
like the combination
of light and sound.

00:13:46.660 --> 00:13:48.130
So when I play
this video, this is

00:13:48.130 --> 00:13:51.130
something we worked on
for BBC many years ago,

00:13:51.130 --> 00:13:53.212
and it's called
the McGurk effect.

00:13:53.212 --> 00:13:55.420
And so when I play the sound,
