00:22:22.601 --> 00:22:23.100
BEAU LOTTO: Right.

00:22:23.100 --> 00:22:24.790
And when things don't
go quite our way,

00:22:24.790 --> 00:22:26.710
we also get a bit
annoyed, right?

00:22:26.710 --> 00:22:29.710
Now you're probably thinking,
I'm not like a frog.

00:22:29.710 --> 00:22:31.530
I've got free will.

00:22:31.530 --> 00:22:32.500
They might be frogs.

00:22:32.500 --> 00:22:33.250
I'm not a frog.

00:22:33.250 --> 00:22:33.700
I have free will.

00:22:33.700 --> 00:22:35.283
So we're going to
test your free will.

00:22:35.283 --> 00:22:38.010
We're going to see if I can read
everybody's mind in this room,

00:22:38.010 --> 00:22:40.900
right all at the same
time by predicting

00:22:40.900 --> 00:22:42.940
what name you're
going to give two

00:22:42.940 --> 00:22:45.312
completely arbitrary shapes.

00:22:45.312 --> 00:22:46.520
These are meaningless shapes.

00:22:46.520 --> 00:22:48.270
They're not circles,
diamonds, or squares.

00:22:48.270 --> 00:22:49.870
They have no name, agreed?

00:22:49.870 --> 00:22:50.620
Yes?

00:22:50.620 --> 00:22:51.160
OK.

00:22:51.160 --> 00:22:54.040
I'm going to give you two
completely arbitrary sounds.

00:22:54.040 --> 00:22:57.460
One is kiki and the
other is booboo, right?

00:22:57.460 --> 00:22:59.417
They also don't mean anything.

00:22:59.417 --> 00:23:01.250
Now you're independent,
freethinking people.

00:23:01.250 --> 00:23:04.360
Tell me, which of these shapes,
which has no name, is kiki,

00:23:04.360 --> 00:23:06.350
and which of these
shapes is booboo?

00:23:06.350 --> 00:23:06.850
Right?

00:23:06.850 --> 00:23:08.110
AUDIENCE: Kiki on the left.

00:23:08.110 --> 00:23:09.818
BEAU LOTTO: How many
on the right-- yeah,

00:23:09.818 --> 00:23:12.490
say booboo's on the right
and kiki's on the left, yes?

00:23:12.490 --> 00:23:14.590
How many of you want
to say the opposite?

00:23:14.590 --> 00:23:17.140
So I read your minds, right?

00:23:17.140 --> 00:23:19.160
Why is this happening?

00:23:19.160 --> 00:23:22.464
Why do you associate
them this way?

00:23:22.464 --> 00:23:23.130
It's the shapes.

00:23:23.130 --> 00:23:24.300
What is it about the shapes?

00:23:24.300 --> 00:23:26.447
AUDIENCE: Shape of the
letters [INAUDIBLE]

00:23:26.447 --> 00:23:28.530
BEAU LOTTO: It could be
the shapes of the letters.

00:23:28.530 --> 00:23:31.140
It actually has to do
with the sharpness, right?

00:23:31.140 --> 00:23:34.720
It has to do with actually
your perception of pain.

00:23:34.720 --> 00:23:36.220
Your brain has an
overrepresentation

00:23:36.220 --> 00:23:38.320
of roundness and
sharpness because it was

00:23:38.320 --> 00:23:41.280
behaviorally useful to do so.

00:23:41.280 --> 00:23:45.120
And kiki and booboo are
sharp and rounded sounds.

00:23:45.120 --> 00:23:48.780
So if I give you the word
love and hate, how many of you

00:23:48.780 --> 00:23:51.510
say the one on the right is
love and the one on the left

00:23:51.510 --> 00:23:52.260
is hate?

00:23:52.260 --> 00:23:52.920
Yes?

00:23:52.920 --> 00:23:56.130
Depending on the state of
your relationship, right?

00:23:56.130 --> 00:23:56.910
Right?

00:23:56.910 --> 00:24:00.270
Because if I give you the word
hate and I prick your finger,

00:24:00.270 --> 00:24:02.760
I activate the same
part of your brain,

00:24:02.760 --> 00:24:06.200
because hate is
actually painful.

00:24:06.200 --> 00:24:09.710
It's the behavioral
significance of the word

00:24:09.710 --> 00:24:12.050
that your brain is
encoding, right?

00:24:12.050 --> 00:24:15.230
And it's behavioral [INAUDIBLE]
of those sharp corners, which

00:24:15.230 --> 00:24:16.901
is pain.

00:24:16.901 --> 00:24:17.400
OK?

00:24:17.400 --> 00:24:18.850
This is the basis of metaphor.

00:24:18.850 --> 00:24:20.280
You're mapping meanings.

00:24:20.280 --> 00:24:22.620
You're not mapping data.

00:24:22.620 --> 00:24:25.880
So if this is true, if
everything that I see

00:24:25.880 --> 00:24:29.376
is grounded in my history,
and what that history gives

00:24:29.376 --> 00:24:31.250
me are assumptions, and
those assumptions are

00:24:31.250 --> 00:24:34.280
essential for my survival--
every time I take a step,

00:24:34.280 --> 00:24:35.854
my brain has all
kinds of assumptions

00:24:35.854 --> 00:24:37.520
that the floor is not
going to give way,

00:24:37.520 --> 00:24:38.936
my legs aren't
going to give away.

00:24:38.936 --> 00:24:41.600
These are essential
for our survival.

00:24:41.600 --> 00:24:43.760
But the problem is,
the world changes.

00:24:43.760 --> 00:24:45.470
So what was once
useful may no longer

00:24:45.470 --> 00:24:50.270
be useful, so we have to
change our assumptions.

00:24:50.270 --> 00:24:53.780
And that's the basis for
how we see differently.

00:24:53.780 --> 00:24:57.930
Change your assumptions, and
you'll change your perception.

00:24:57.930 --> 00:24:58.500
Right?

00:24:58.500 --> 00:25:02.160
If your space of possibility is
determined by your assumptions,

00:25:02.160 --> 00:25:04.320
if what lies right next
to me is determined

00:25:04.320 --> 00:25:06.979
by what I assume to
be true, by changing

00:25:06.979 --> 00:25:08.520
what I assume to be
true, I'll change

00:25:08.520 --> 00:25:11.130
what lies right next to me, OK?

00:25:11.130 --> 00:25:13.590
I'm going to show you how
powerful this is, simply

00:25:13.590 --> 00:25:16.305
in the context of
perceived motion.

00:25:16.305 --> 00:25:18.680
So as I put this into motion,
you'll probably assume it's

00:25:18.680 --> 00:25:20.870
spinning from left
to right, yes?

00:25:20.870 --> 00:25:24.460
That's because your brain
has the assumption that it

00:25:24.460 --> 00:25:26.167
looks down onto surfaces.

00:25:26.167 --> 00:25:28.000
We come into the world
with this assumption,

00:25:28.000 --> 00:25:29.860
with this bias,
in the same way we

00:25:29.860 --> 00:25:31.485
come into the world
with the assumption

00:25:31.485 --> 00:25:33.310
that light comes from above, OK?

00:25:33.310 --> 00:25:36.070
We incorporate the laws of
physics into our perception.

00:25:36.070 --> 00:25:37.474
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:25:40.290 --> 00:25:43.150
BEAU LOTTO: We'll
come to that, OK?

00:25:43.150 --> 00:25:46.030
So for most of you, the
most likely perception,

00:25:46.030 --> 00:25:48.100
given the assumption, it's
because your brain has

00:25:48.100 --> 00:25:50.183
a different assumption,
which you're not aware of,

00:25:50.183 --> 00:25:51.880
but I'll make it
explicit in a second.

00:25:51.880 --> 00:25:52.380
Sorry?

00:25:52.380 --> 00:25:53.297
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:25:53.297 --> 00:25:54.921
BEAU LOTTO: But the
explicit assumption

00:25:54.921 --> 00:25:57.520
is that you're actually looking
up at the surface, not down.

00:25:57.520 --> 00:25:58.555
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:25:58.555 --> 00:25:59.950
BEAU LOTTO: It could be.

00:25:59.950 --> 00:26:00.490
It could be.

00:26:03.190 --> 00:26:06.182
So most of you will assume
that your brain is actually

00:26:06.182 --> 00:26:07.390
looking down to that surface.

00:26:07.390 --> 00:26:09.015
If you're looking
down at that surface,

00:26:09.015 --> 00:26:11.090
then the most likely
perception is left to right.

00:26:11.090 --> 00:26:13.090
The possibility that it's
spinning right to left

00:26:13.090 --> 00:26:16.810
is actually impossible
given that assumption.

00:26:16.810 --> 00:26:20.976
But if I put into
motion, and you

00:26:20.976 --> 00:26:22.350
try to play with
your assumption,

00:26:22.350 --> 00:26:24.780
challenge your assumption,
imagine looking up

00:26:24.780 --> 00:26:26.490
at it instead of
down, it will then

00:26:26.490 --> 00:26:30.720
go in the opposite
direction, right?

00:26:30.720 --> 00:26:33.210
So sometimes if you
blur your eyes, blink,

00:26:33.210 --> 00:26:34.637
you can get it to flip.

00:26:34.637 --> 00:26:36.720
So can you get it to go
in the opposite direction,

00:26:36.720 --> 00:26:38.940
or do you have it just going
in that same direction?

00:26:38.940 --> 00:26:40.380
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:26:44.364 --> 00:26:45.030
BEAU LOTTO: Yes.

00:26:45.030 --> 00:26:47.287
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:26:47.287 --> 00:26:48.120
BEAU LOTTO: Exactly.

00:26:48.120 --> 00:26:49.371
Can you get it to flip though?

00:26:49.371 --> 00:26:50.286
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:26:50.286 --> 00:26:51.000
BEAU LOTTO: Yeah.

00:26:51.000 --> 00:26:53.714
But the reason why it's flipping
is-- can you get it to flip?

00:26:53.714 --> 00:26:54.880
Who else can get it to flip?

00:26:54.880 --> 00:26:55.762
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:26:55.762 --> 00:26:56.470
BEAU LOTTO: Yeah?

00:26:56.470 --> 00:27:00.906
Blur your eyes and blink
and look around it.

00:27:00.906 --> 00:27:02.360
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:27:02.360 --> 00:27:03.141
BEAU LOTTO: Yeah.

00:27:03.141 --> 00:27:03.640
OK.

00:27:03.640 --> 00:27:04.530
AUDIENCE: There we go.

00:27:04.530 --> 00:27:04.960
BEAU LOTTO: You get it?

00:27:04.960 --> 00:27:06.310
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:27:06.310 --> 00:27:07.060
BEAU LOTTO: OK.

00:27:07.060 --> 00:27:09.060
What's happening is
basically, when you assume--

00:27:09.060 --> 00:27:10.976
when your brain has the
assumption that you're

00:27:10.976 --> 00:27:13.540
looking down onto the surface,
the most likely interpretation

00:27:13.540 --> 00:27:15.550
is left to right, right?

00:27:15.550 --> 00:27:17.830
Given that assumption.

00:27:17.830 --> 00:27:20.380
As soon as you change that
assumption that you're

00:27:20.380 --> 00:27:22.780
looking up at it, the most
likely perception is it's

00:27:22.780 --> 00:27:25.330
spinning the opposite
direction, from right to left.

00:27:25.330 --> 00:27:28.680
What was previously
possible becomes impossible.

00:27:28.680 --> 00:27:31.330
You can no longer see it
spinning from left to right

00:27:31.330 --> 00:27:33.109
because you've changed
your perception.

00:27:33.109 --> 00:27:35.650
And every time you switch your
perception, what your brain is

00:27:35.650 --> 00:27:37.780
doing is changing its
assumption of whether it's

00:27:37.780 --> 00:27:41.260
looking up or down, because
it has a different meaning

00:27:41.260 --> 00:27:43.270
depending on that assumption.

00:27:43.270 --> 00:27:46.000
While the stimulus might
be bistable mathematically,

00:27:46.000 --> 00:27:48.190
it's not bistable in your head.

00:27:48.190 --> 00:27:51.550
It's determined by what
assumptions you're making.

00:27:51.550 --> 00:27:53.830
So what was once impossible
becomes possible.

00:27:53.830 --> 00:27:56.660
Once possible becomes
the impossible.

00:27:56.660 --> 00:27:59.030
All you're doing is
changing your assumptions.

00:27:59.030 --> 00:28:01.040
And we're just
talking about motion.

00:28:01.040 --> 00:28:04.120
This is what creativity is.

00:28:04.120 --> 00:28:06.100
Your brain never does big jumps.

00:28:06.100 --> 00:28:09.100
It never brings two things
that are far apart together.

00:28:09.100 --> 00:28:12.430
It only ever makes
a small step, right?

00:28:12.430 --> 00:28:16.510
But it changes what's next to
it by changing its search space,

00:28:16.510 --> 00:28:20.419
by changing the assumptions
that define that search space.

00:28:20.419 --> 00:28:22.960
So a quick question, which is,
which direction is it actually

00:28:22.960 --> 00:28:25.060
rotating?

00:28:25.060 --> 00:28:27.520
How many think left to right?

00:28:27.520 --> 00:28:28.870
Right to left?

00:28:28.870 --> 00:28:30.830
I don't care.

00:28:30.830 --> 00:28:33.850
There's no motion on
the screen at all.

00:28:33.850 --> 00:28:37.200
There's literally no motion.

00:28:37.200 --> 00:28:39.690
Agreed?

00:28:39.690 --> 00:28:40.260
No?

00:28:40.260 --> 00:28:42.450
I mean, it's an
animation, right?

00:28:42.450 --> 00:28:44.460
You're looking at a
series of still images

00:28:44.460 --> 00:28:46.380
that are slightly
different from each other.

00:28:46.380 --> 00:28:48.999
Your brain is taking
that small change

00:28:48.999 --> 00:28:50.790
and seeing the meaning
of the change, which

00:28:50.790 --> 00:28:52.720
we call fine motion.

00:28:52.720 --> 00:28:55.860
If I took all those images and
put them in random sequence,

00:28:55.860 --> 00:28:58.580
you would simply see a flicker.

00:28:58.580 --> 00:29:03.120
So you're seeing the meaning
of the change, not the change.

00:29:03.120 --> 00:29:03.640
OK.

00:29:03.640 --> 00:29:07.240
So this idea that "creativity
is this chaotic, messy,

00:29:07.240 --> 00:29:09.582
serendipitous process"
is predicated on the idea

00:29:09.582 --> 00:29:12.040
that the brain puts two things
that are far apart together,

00:29:12.040 --> 00:29:14.090
that it actually
jumps, teleports

00:29:14.090 --> 00:29:16.120
within its search space.

00:29:16.120 --> 00:29:18.910
That's not how
adaptive systems work.

00:29:18.910 --> 00:29:22.550
They only ever do small steps.

00:29:22.550 --> 00:29:26.140
So if that's true,
then in fact, there's

00:29:26.140 --> 00:29:28.090
nothing creative
about creativity.

00:29:28.090 --> 00:29:30.397
It's only creative
from the outside.

00:29:30.397 --> 00:29:32.230
When you see someone
putting two things that

00:29:32.230 --> 00:29:34.960
are far apart together,
it's because for you, they

00:29:34.960 --> 00:29:36.280
are far apart together.

00:29:36.280 --> 00:29:38.710
You have a different
search space.

00:29:38.710 --> 00:29:41.140
For them, they're
making not a simple,

00:29:41.140 --> 00:29:43.750
but they're making
a logical next step,

00:29:43.750 --> 00:29:46.540
consciously or unconsciously,
to the next most likely

00:29:46.540 --> 00:29:49.120
possible based on
their search space,

00:29:49.120 --> 00:29:51.484
which is based on
their assumptions.

00:29:51.484 --> 00:29:53.150
Because they have
different assumptions,

00:29:53.150 --> 00:29:56.529
a different history, they have
a different search space, Right?

00:29:56.529 --> 00:29:57.320
And you think, wow.

00:29:57.320 --> 00:29:58.340
How did they do that?

00:29:58.340 --> 00:30:00.840
How did they bring those two
things that far apart together?

00:30:00.840 --> 00:30:02.150
Again, for you, they are.

00:30:02.150 --> 00:30:04.160
For them, they're not.

00:30:04.160 --> 00:30:06.950
So creativity is this
process of taking small steps

00:30:06.950 --> 00:30:09.320
to the next most
likely, changing

00:30:09.320 --> 00:30:13.330
your space of possibility by
questioning your assumptions.

00:30:13.330 --> 00:30:15.310
OK?

00:30:15.310 --> 00:30:17.290
And that's the basis
for how we change

00:30:17.290 --> 00:30:22.200
our assumptions, which is all
revolutions begin with a joke.

00:30:22.200 --> 00:30:24.420
They begin with a question.

00:30:24.420 --> 00:30:26.460
Nothing interesting
begins with knowing.

00:30:26.460 --> 00:30:29.840
It begins with not knowing.

00:30:29.840 --> 00:30:31.280
It doesn't begin with an answer.

00:30:31.280 --> 00:30:35.526
It begins with a question, and
it begins with a good question.

00:30:35.526 --> 00:30:37.400
You could be a great
experimentalist, come up

00:30:37.400 --> 00:30:39.170
with a great
experimental design.

00:30:39.170 --> 00:30:42.230
But if you're asking a
bad question, who cares?

00:30:42.230 --> 00:30:44.735
The cash is in a good
question, not necessarily

00:30:44.735 --> 00:30:47.907
in the right answer, right?

00:30:47.907 --> 00:30:49.740
So if you're actually
wanting to get someone

00:30:49.740 --> 00:30:52.930
to shift from A to
B, the first step

00:30:52.930 --> 00:30:58.370
is not actually B. The
first step is just to stop.

00:30:58.370 --> 00:31:01.610
The first step is to stop
the association that you're

00:31:01.610 --> 00:31:03.500
making with that stimulus.

00:31:03.500 --> 00:31:08.490
The first step is to go to
not A. If what I'm doing

00:31:08.490 --> 00:31:10.200
is I get a stimulus
and I automatically

00:31:10.200 --> 00:31:13.290
generate a meaning,
the first step is not

00:31:13.290 --> 00:31:14.640
to create a new meaning.

00:31:14.640 --> 00:31:19.470
The first step is to not make
that meaning, to go to not A.

00:31:19.470 --> 00:31:22.150
And then once you're in
that space of uncertainty,

00:31:22.150 --> 00:31:25.860
now you can go in
multiple directions.

00:31:25.860 --> 00:31:30.400
So you can control the process
of going to not A, right?

00:31:30.400 --> 00:31:33.400
But you can't control
where you go next.

00:31:33.400 --> 00:31:36.260
And we'll come to the
importance of ecology

00:31:36.260 --> 00:31:39.550
for where you go next after, OK?

00:31:39.550 --> 00:31:42.340
But if this is true, if asking
questions, and in particular,

00:31:42.340 --> 00:31:44.950
good questions is the
basis of creativity,

00:31:44.950 --> 00:31:48.510
why is it so difficult
to ask a good question?

00:31:48.510 --> 00:31:50.770
Why is that so hard for us?

00:31:50.770 --> 00:31:53.710
I'm going to suggest two
main reasons for this.

00:31:53.710 --> 00:31:56.320
There are others, but
these are two main reasons.

00:31:56.320 --> 00:31:58.474
And the first one
is that we often

00:31:58.474 --> 00:31:59.890
walk through life
thinking we have

00:31:59.890 --> 00:32:03.860
an objective view of the world,
that we're rational, right?

00:32:03.860 --> 00:32:05.860
That we have no
assumptions and biases.

00:32:05.860 --> 00:32:09.400
Or we'll admit that sometimes we
do, it's just that not always.

00:32:09.400 --> 00:32:11.260
But the point here
is every time you

00:32:11.260 --> 00:32:12.760
make a perception
or a behavior, you

00:32:12.760 --> 00:32:14.109
have biases and assumptions.

00:32:14.109 --> 00:32:15.400
You can never escape from them.

00:32:15.400 --> 00:32:17.350
You can change them,
but you can never

00:32:17.350 --> 00:32:22.050
escape from having
assumptions and biases, right?

00:32:22.050 --> 00:32:26.420
So here's a game you can play
when you have people around

00:32:26.420 --> 00:32:28.970
for dinner, and you can do
it as a thought experiment

00:32:28.970 --> 00:32:32.840
right now to demonstrate the
irrationality of who we are.

00:32:32.840 --> 00:32:35.290
Imagine you have
a glass of water,

00:32:35.290 --> 00:32:40.460
and imagine spitting inside
your glass of water, right?

00:32:40.460 --> 00:32:42.780
So do this at home when you
have friends around, right?

00:32:42.780 --> 00:32:43.280
Imagine--

00:32:43.280 --> 00:32:44.180
[LAUGHTER]

00:32:44.180 --> 00:32:47.450
--imagine spitting into
your glass of water, right?

00:32:47.450 --> 00:32:51.490
So now imagine drinking it.

00:32:51.490 --> 00:32:53.457
Do you get a sense of disgust?

00:32:53.457 --> 00:32:55.040
But it's completely
irrational, right?

00:32:55.040 --> 00:32:56.790
What was once in your
mouth, you're simply

00:32:56.790 --> 00:32:58.640
putting right back in, right?

00:32:58.640 --> 00:33:01.400
It's just part of you, right?

00:33:01.400 --> 00:33:04.719
But we can't help but generate
this perception of disgust,

00:33:04.719 --> 00:33:06.260
even though it's
completely rational.

00:33:06.260 --> 00:33:07.850
AUDIENCE: Kids wouldn't
mind to do that.

00:33:07.850 --> 00:33:08.150
BEAU LOTTO: Sorry?

00:33:08.150 --> 00:33:09.470
AUDIENCE: Kids wouldn't
mind to do that.

00:33:09.470 --> 00:33:10.940
BEAU LOTTO: No, kids
would be fine with it.

00:33:10.940 --> 00:33:12.481
Even if it was
someone else's saliva,

00:33:12.481 --> 00:33:14.420
they'd be fine with it, right?

00:33:14.420 --> 00:33:15.110
Right?

00:33:15.110 --> 00:33:17.900
So everything you do has a bias.

00:33:17.900 --> 00:33:21.465
Everything you do has
an assumption, OK?

00:33:21.465 --> 00:33:23.840
But the other problem is that
these assumptions are often

00:33:23.840 --> 00:33:25.400
hidden to us.

00:33:25.400 --> 00:33:28.010
We often have no idea
why we do what we do,

00:33:28.010 --> 00:33:30.290
in the same way you didn't
know why you necessarily

00:33:30.290 --> 00:33:34.420
named those two shapes
kiki and booboo.

00:33:34.420 --> 00:33:36.422
Our assumptions are
often hidden to us,

00:33:36.422 --> 00:33:37.630
and here's an example of one.

00:33:37.630 --> 00:33:38.230
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:33:38.230 --> 00:33:39.979
- So there's nothing
Barack Obama could do

00:33:39.979 --> 00:33:41.620
to prove that he was born here.

00:33:41.620 --> 00:33:44.110
- If there was
maybe witnesses that

00:33:44.110 --> 00:33:46.180
were in attendance at his birth.

00:33:46.180 --> 00:33:46.930
- Like his mother?

00:33:46.930 --> 00:33:48.221
Would you listen to his mother?

00:33:48.221 --> 00:33:48.770
- No, no, no.

00:33:48.770 --> 00:33:50.010
She has motivation to lie.

00:33:50.010 --> 00:33:52.690
- So you don't trust Donald
Trump's birth certificate

00:33:52.690 --> 00:33:53.400
either?

00:33:53.400 --> 00:33:55.500
- Uh, yeah, because
he's been here forever.

00:33:55.500 --> 00:33:56.500
- Well, how do you know?

00:33:56.500 --> 00:33:57.958
But how do you--
what's your proof?

00:33:57.958 --> 00:33:59.720
- Um, well, his parents and--

00:33:59.720 --> 00:34:00.940
- But no, they're biased.

00:34:00.940 --> 00:34:02.030
I'm talking about,
