00:34:06.440 --> 00:34:07.120
[END PLAYBACK]

00:34:07.120 --> 00:34:07.870
BEAU LOTTO: Right?

00:34:07.870 --> 00:34:09.909
[LAUGHTER]

00:34:09.909 --> 00:34:13.840
And we laugh, but we're
no different, right?

00:34:13.840 --> 00:34:15.280
Everything we do
are assumptions,

00:34:15.280 --> 00:34:18.639
and we often don't
know that we're

00:34:18.639 --> 00:34:20.401
being guided, our
decisions, our choices

00:34:20.401 --> 00:34:22.150
are being guided by
these assumptions that

00:34:22.150 --> 00:34:24.699
are almost blind to us, right?

00:34:24.699 --> 00:34:27.050
We're blind to them, right?

00:34:27.050 --> 00:34:30.699
Hence the power of
diversity of groups.

00:34:30.699 --> 00:34:33.659
So diversity of groups have
at least two significances.

00:34:33.659 --> 00:34:36.540
First of all, the best person
to reveal your own assumptions

00:34:36.540 --> 00:34:38.670
to you is rarely you.

00:34:38.670 --> 00:34:42.940
It's usually someone else in
the right kind of environment.

00:34:42.940 --> 00:34:44.880
So if you give me
two groups, one

00:34:44.880 --> 00:34:47.606
average to lower IQ from
a more diverse background,

00:34:47.606 --> 00:34:49.730
versus another group which
has a higher average IQ,

00:34:49.730 --> 00:34:53.670
but from the same background,
I want the first group, right?

00:34:53.670 --> 00:34:55.505
Because in that group
in the right setting,

00:34:55.505 --> 00:34:57.630
they're more likely to
reveal their own assumptions

00:34:57.630 --> 00:34:58.770
to each other.

00:34:58.770 --> 00:35:01.710
What's more, the search
space of that group

00:35:01.710 --> 00:35:03.845
is much more complex.

00:35:03.845 --> 00:35:05.470
It's a higher
dimensional search space,

00:35:05.470 --> 00:35:07.280
because they have more
diverse assumptions.

00:35:07.280 --> 00:35:09.230
And we know from
complex systems theory

00:35:09.230 --> 00:35:11.650
that the best solutions
are more likely to exist

00:35:11.650 --> 00:35:14.950
in a more complex search space
than in a simpler search space.

00:35:14.950 --> 00:35:19.180
A simpler search space is more
adaptable, more evolvable,

00:35:19.180 --> 00:35:23.230
but it's actually less likely
to hold the best solution.

00:35:23.230 --> 00:35:25.210
So I want the first group.

00:35:25.210 --> 00:35:27.100
I discover what my
assumptions are,

00:35:27.100 --> 00:35:29.260
and I can occupy within
a more complex search

00:35:29.260 --> 00:35:34.230
space in the right environment,
which I'll come to in a moment.

00:35:34.230 --> 00:35:36.580
And the kind of search space
and the kind of combination

00:35:36.580 --> 00:35:40.060
diversity that we tend to work
with is expert with naive.

00:35:40.060 --> 00:35:44.050
And the reason is because
experts are super efficient,

00:35:44.050 --> 00:35:47.110
but they're terrible
asking a good question.

00:35:47.110 --> 00:35:49.690
But what's ironic is they
can recognize a good question

00:35:49.690 --> 00:35:51.720
when asked.

00:35:51.720 --> 00:35:56.190
Whereas people who are naive,
they can ask great questions,

00:35:56.190 --> 00:35:58.830
but they don't know
they're great questions.

00:35:58.830 --> 00:36:02.036
So we find it's a
great combination.

00:36:02.036 --> 00:36:03.660
And also the power
of actually stepping

00:36:03.660 --> 00:36:06.690
into a space which is
different from what you know.

00:36:06.690 --> 00:36:09.960
So you can actually shift
yourself from expert and naive,

00:36:09.960 --> 00:36:10.995
and back and forth.

00:36:10.995 --> 00:36:15.440
So you can occupy both ways
of being at the same time.

00:36:15.440 --> 00:36:17.840
So both in groups,
but also internally.

00:36:17.840 --> 00:36:19.720
It is the combination
of expert and naive.

00:36:19.720 --> 00:36:21.240
And also, think
about technology.

00:36:21.240 --> 00:36:23.340
It's obviously here.

00:36:23.340 --> 00:36:26.370
So what defines the
best technology?

00:36:26.370 --> 00:36:28.290
One argument is
that it's not what

00:36:28.290 --> 00:36:30.730
enables us to do what we
can already do faster,

00:36:30.730 --> 00:36:32.190
easier, with less friction.

00:36:32.190 --> 00:36:33.480
Those are good technologies.

00:36:33.480 --> 00:36:34.470
They're useful.

00:36:34.470 --> 00:36:37.040
They're not necessary
transformative.

00:36:37.040 --> 00:36:39.140
What are the ones that
are transformative?

00:36:39.140 --> 00:36:42.780
I'd suggest they make
the invisible visible.

00:36:42.780 --> 00:36:46.210
They enable us to see what
we couldn't see before.

00:36:46.210 --> 00:36:48.940
A microscope, a telescope, MRI.

00:36:48.940 --> 00:36:50.430
Even a book.

00:36:50.430 --> 00:36:53.680
Being able to travel to
a new culture, right?

00:36:53.680 --> 00:36:56.440
Because not only does that
reveal our own assumptions

00:36:56.440 --> 00:36:57.220
to ourselves.

00:36:57.220 --> 00:37:03.030
It enables us to expand the
complexity of our assumptions.

00:37:03.030 --> 00:37:05.580
To shift from being the
center of the universe

00:37:05.580 --> 00:37:08.490
to then revolving around,
orbiting around the sun,

00:37:08.490 --> 00:37:10.140
completely changed
our assumptions

00:37:10.140 --> 00:37:12.880
of what it was to be human.

00:37:12.880 --> 00:37:15.220
Those are transformative
technologies

00:37:15.220 --> 00:37:19.280
that enable us to see what
we couldn't see previously.

00:37:19.280 --> 00:37:22.090
Which is why creativity
actually begins with humility.

00:37:22.090 --> 00:37:24.900
It begins with not knowing.

00:37:24.900 --> 00:37:27.182
So actually, one of
my aims in this talk

00:37:27.182 --> 00:37:28.890
is that you know less
at the end than you

00:37:28.890 --> 00:37:31.170
think you know now, right?

00:37:31.170 --> 00:37:34.050
Because nothing interesting
begins with knowing.

00:37:34.050 --> 00:37:36.700
It begins with not knowing.

00:37:36.700 --> 00:37:38.590
So the second one, and
the most difficult,

00:37:38.590 --> 00:37:41.890
is it might be that you now
accept that everything you do

00:37:41.890 --> 00:37:45.640
has a bias and an
assumption, and that you're

00:37:45.640 --> 00:37:47.470
going to now try to
reveal what they are

00:37:47.470 --> 00:37:50.590
to yourself or through others.

00:37:50.590 --> 00:37:54.410
But now you have the next step,
which is to question them.

00:37:54.410 --> 00:37:59.270
But we hate not knowing, because
to question an assumption,

00:37:59.270 --> 00:38:01.700
especially the assumptions
that define who you are,

00:38:01.700 --> 00:38:03.740
puts you into uncertainty.

00:38:03.740 --> 00:38:06.320
And we hate uncertainty.

00:38:06.320 --> 00:38:09.290
To not be sure that was a
predator, it's too late.

00:38:09.290 --> 00:38:11.390
Your brain evolved to
take what is uncertain

00:38:11.390 --> 00:38:13.370
and to make it certain.

00:38:13.370 --> 00:38:15.020
So when you go down
below in a boat

00:38:15.020 --> 00:38:16.670
and you're either moving
relative to the boat,

00:38:16.670 --> 00:38:18.700
your eyes are saying,
oh, we're standing still.

00:38:18.700 --> 00:38:20.324
But your inner ears
are saying, no, no.

00:38:20.324 --> 00:38:20.960
We're moving.

00:38:20.960 --> 00:38:22.876
And your brain cannot
deal with that conflict,

00:38:22.876 --> 00:38:25.070
which is one of the reasons
why you get seasick.

00:38:25.070 --> 00:38:27.330
So you go above deck and
you watch the horizon,

00:38:27.330 --> 00:38:30.080
so your eyes and inner ears
are moving in register.

00:38:30.080 --> 00:38:36.860
We hate uncertainty,
because dying is easy.

00:38:36.860 --> 00:38:39.350
To step into uncertainty
is literally-- to not know

00:38:39.350 --> 00:38:40.940
throughout evolution
was to increase

00:38:40.940 --> 00:38:42.890
the probability of dying.

00:38:42.890 --> 00:38:44.490
Your brain evolved to predict.

00:38:44.490 --> 00:38:46.490
The better it's able to
predict, the more likely

00:38:46.490 --> 00:38:48.972
it is able to survive.

00:38:48.972 --> 00:38:50.870
OK?

00:38:50.870 --> 00:38:53.300
And what's more,
the best questions

00:38:53.300 --> 00:38:55.710
create the most uncertainty.

00:38:55.710 --> 00:38:58.830
So for instance, imagine we
were remodel your biases,

00:38:58.830 --> 00:39:01.347
your assumptions as
a network, right?

00:39:01.347 --> 00:39:03.430
Which we could do with the
gene regulatory network

00:39:03.430 --> 00:39:04.540
or your biases, right?

00:39:04.540 --> 00:39:08.710
And in the upper left, those
are your biases that are not

00:39:08.710 --> 00:39:10.402
connected to each other, right?

00:39:10.402 --> 00:39:11.860
It'd be like a gene
that's encoding

00:39:11.860 --> 00:39:14.210
the color of your eyes, OK?

00:39:14.210 --> 00:39:16.180
Now if we're to
question that bias

00:39:16.180 --> 00:39:19.600
and metaphorically move
it, nothing else changes.

00:39:19.600 --> 00:39:22.060
Just that bias.

00:39:22.060 --> 00:39:25.090
Now imagine instead
you question a bias,

00:39:25.090 --> 00:39:27.010
you move a bias
that's fully connected

00:39:27.010 --> 00:39:29.890
to all your other assumptions,
something that maybe

00:39:29.890 --> 00:39:31.945
defines what it is to be you.

00:39:31.945 --> 00:39:33.320
That would be an
example of, say,

00:39:33.320 --> 00:39:37.180
a homeobox gene that determines
segmentation of the body.

00:39:37.180 --> 00:39:39.010
If you shift that by--
it's the same amount

00:39:39.010 --> 00:39:41.530
of energy, same
amount of movement,

00:39:41.530 --> 00:39:45.270
the whole system shifts.

00:39:45.270 --> 00:39:47.160
This is what we call
in complex systems

00:39:47.160 --> 00:39:49.550
a point of self-criticality.

00:39:49.550 --> 00:39:52.560
And we experience this
in nature all the time.

00:39:52.560 --> 00:39:53.910
Here's an example.

00:39:53.910 --> 00:39:57.350
This snow bank is under a
tremendous amount of tension,

00:39:57.350 --> 00:39:58.760
because it's fully connected.

00:39:58.760 --> 00:40:01.010
You add a small
amount of weight,

00:40:01.010 --> 00:40:05.000
and the whole thing gives way.

00:40:05.000 --> 00:40:13.697
So great questions can cause
massive shifts in uncertainty.

00:40:13.697 --> 00:40:16.030
And now you're all wondering
whether or not he survived.

00:40:16.030 --> 00:40:16.655
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:40:16.655 --> 00:40:17.363
BEAU LOTTO: Yeah.

00:40:17.363 --> 00:40:19.120
I'm not going to tell
you just yet, right?

00:40:19.120 --> 00:40:23.734
Because you are experiencing
uncertainty, right?

00:40:23.734 --> 00:40:25.150
That's what it is
being uncertain.

00:40:25.150 --> 00:40:26.830
You want to know, right?

00:40:26.830 --> 00:40:30.430
We hate not knowing and
sitting with that moment

00:40:30.430 --> 00:40:31.990
of not knowing.

00:40:31.990 --> 00:40:35.290
And yet, the irony is
that's the only place

00:40:35.290 --> 00:40:38.500
you can go if you're ever
going to be creative,

00:40:38.500 --> 00:40:40.950
is to step into uncertainty.

00:40:40.950 --> 00:40:43.730
And again, to be in uncertainty
creates a tremendous amount

00:40:43.730 --> 00:40:44.230
of stress.

00:40:44.230 --> 00:40:46.080
That's one of our
biggest sources

00:40:46.080 --> 00:40:50.460
of unwellness in our world
is the speed and uncertainty,

00:40:50.460 --> 00:40:51.240
right?

00:40:51.240 --> 00:40:53.940
It actually decreases
connectivity within the brain,

00:40:53.940 --> 00:40:57.055
decreases adaptability,
increases brain cell death.

00:40:57.055 --> 00:40:59.430
It actually makes you a more
extreme version of yourself.

00:40:59.430 --> 00:41:01.080
If you're a liberal,
you become more liberal.

00:41:01.080 --> 00:41:03.371
If you're a conservative,
you become more conservative.

00:41:03.371 --> 00:41:05.970
You go to a place
that is familiar.

00:41:05.970 --> 00:41:08.010
Almost every
behavior you do, you

00:41:08.010 --> 00:41:11.409
do in order to
increase certainty.

00:41:11.409 --> 00:41:13.200
You could argue it's
one of the reasons why

00:41:13.200 --> 00:41:15.330
Uber was originally successful.

00:41:15.330 --> 00:41:18.700
Not because they enabled
you to order a taxi easier.

00:41:18.700 --> 00:41:22.740
It's because they told you when
the taxi was going to arrive.

00:41:22.740 --> 00:41:25.180
If I put you in San Francisco
on the street corner

00:41:25.180 --> 00:41:29.435
and you're trying to catch a
taxi, and after five minutes,

00:41:29.435 --> 00:41:31.560
all these are going by,
you're completely stressed,

00:41:31.560 --> 00:41:33.300
your cortisol
levels are going up.

00:41:33.300 --> 00:41:34.685
And finally, you get a taxi.

00:41:34.685 --> 00:41:36.810
Now if instead I sit you
on the same street corner,

00:41:36.810 --> 00:41:38.268
and after five
minutes I say, don't

00:41:38.268 --> 00:41:40.455
worry, it'll be there
in five minutes, right?

00:41:40.455 --> 00:41:42.330
You're using your phone,
your cortisol levels

00:41:42.330 --> 00:41:43.690
go down, et cetera.

00:41:43.690 --> 00:41:44.870
Right?

00:41:44.870 --> 00:41:47.310
It's because of uncertainty.

00:41:47.310 --> 00:41:50.490
Which is why in London now, they
put the times on all the bus

00:41:50.490 --> 00:41:51.120
stops.

00:41:51.120 --> 00:41:52.590
Even though it's going
to be an hour and a half

00:41:52.590 --> 00:41:54.030
before the bus gets
there, but knowing it's

00:41:54.030 --> 00:41:56.370
going to be an hour and a
half decreases your stress.

00:41:56.370 --> 00:42:00.450
And at Terminal 5 in Heathrow,
wonderful, classic example.

00:42:00.450 --> 00:42:03.870
You get off the Heathrow
Express, you go into a lift.

00:42:03.870 --> 00:42:05.670
There's only one place
for this lift to go,

00:42:05.670 --> 00:42:07.830
which is one floor
up to departures.

00:42:07.830 --> 00:42:12.040
So you step in, the doors shut,
and now you're trapped, right?

00:42:12.040 --> 00:42:14.920
Because there's no button to
tell you to go to floor one.

00:42:14.920 --> 00:42:17.320
So the first experience of
this millions and millions

00:42:17.320 --> 00:42:20.920
of dollars terminal
was stress, right?

00:42:20.920 --> 00:42:21.950
Because of uncertainty.

00:42:21.950 --> 00:42:22.850
So what did they do?

00:42:22.850 --> 00:42:26.350
They put a little button on the
lift, that when you touched it,

00:42:26.350 --> 00:42:28.705
the light went on, and it was
connected to nothing else.

00:42:28.705 --> 00:42:29.800
[LAUGHTER]

00:42:29.800 --> 00:42:30.517
Right?

00:42:30.517 --> 00:42:31.600
So you walked in the lift.

00:42:31.600 --> 00:42:32.820
You had this sense that, ah.

00:42:32.820 --> 00:42:33.444
Thank goodness.

00:42:33.444 --> 00:42:35.677
Now it goes-- it was always
going to go up, right?

00:42:35.677 --> 00:42:37.760
It was always going to do
exactly what it's doing.

00:42:37.760 --> 00:42:39.426
But you had this sense
of certainty now,

00:42:39.426 --> 00:42:41.080
of familiarity, right?

00:42:41.080 --> 00:42:44.330
We hate uncertainty.

00:42:44.330 --> 00:42:46.600
And again, that's the
only place we can go

00:42:46.600 --> 00:42:48.230
if we're going to be creative.

00:42:48.230 --> 00:42:51.790
So how does the brain
deal with uncertainty?

00:42:51.790 --> 00:42:54.730
Because what's more, that
uncertainty and stress

00:42:54.730 --> 00:42:56.950
reduces your space
of possibility.

00:42:56.950 --> 00:42:59.200
In fact, here's an example
of a space of possibility

00:42:59.200 --> 00:43:01.390
reducing to a single dimension.

00:43:01.390 --> 00:43:02.990
This happened in Australia.

00:43:02.990 --> 00:43:04.570
He's going in to rob a bank.

00:43:04.570 --> 00:43:05.760
This actually happened.

00:43:05.760 --> 00:43:08.110
He hands the teller
a note, right?

00:43:08.110 --> 00:43:09.860
And now suddenly, the
bank gets shut down.

00:43:09.860 --> 00:43:10.970
He's trapped.

00:43:10.970 --> 00:43:12.260
He's stuck, right?

00:43:12.260 --> 00:43:13.760
He's locked in.

00:43:13.760 --> 00:43:16.730
But in fact, he's locked within
a completely narrow space

00:43:16.730 --> 00:43:20.440
of possibility, one
dimension, because he's

00:43:20.440 --> 00:43:25.930
forgotten that doors pull
as well as push, right?

00:43:25.930 --> 00:43:30.400
So he was trapped by his
search space, not by the door.

00:43:30.400 --> 00:43:32.850
He was caught five
minutes later.

00:43:32.850 --> 00:43:33.350
Right?

00:43:33.350 --> 00:43:34.630
AUDIENCE: Wait, so it
wasn't actually locked.

00:43:34.630 --> 00:43:35.838
BEAU LOTTO: It wasn't locked.

00:43:35.838 --> 00:43:37.000
[LAUGHTER]

00:43:37.000 --> 00:43:40.280
The door was always open, but he
was pushing against it, right?

00:43:40.280 --> 00:43:43.600
Because his search space went
down to a single dimension.

00:43:43.600 --> 00:43:47.390
And that's what happens when you
get stressed from uncertainty.

00:43:47.390 --> 00:43:51.932
So how can the brain--
but if the only place

00:43:51.932 --> 00:43:54.140
we can go to be creative is
to step into uncertainty,

00:43:54.140 --> 00:43:58.690
the very place that our brain
evolved to avoid, how is it

00:43:58.690 --> 00:44:00.310
that we can actually go there?

00:44:00.310 --> 00:44:02.400
What is evolution's
solution to uncertainty?

00:44:02.400 --> 00:44:04.300
Because it's essential,
in order to adapt,

00:44:04.300 --> 00:44:05.890
that we're able to go there.

00:44:05.890 --> 00:44:07.420
So evolution gave us a solution.

00:44:07.420 --> 00:44:10.690
So what's the one thing that
you do where you actually

00:44:10.690 --> 00:44:12.010
love uncertainty?

00:44:12.010 --> 00:44:13.330
It's not that you tolerate it.

00:44:13.330 --> 00:44:14.920
You actually seek it.

00:44:14.920 --> 00:44:18.180
What's the one
thing that you do?

00:44:18.180 --> 00:44:19.640
AUDIENCE: Play games.

00:44:19.640 --> 00:44:21.020
BEAU LOTTO: Play.

00:44:21.020 --> 00:44:23.560
Play is evolution's
solution to uncertainty.

00:44:23.560 --> 00:44:26.900
Is why play evolved, right?

00:44:26.900 --> 00:44:31.990
What's more, play is
a way of being, OK?

00:44:31.990 --> 00:44:33.886
It's a way-- for
those who study play,

00:44:33.886 --> 00:44:35.760
it's not just running
around in a playground.

00:44:35.760 --> 00:44:39.320
It is literally a serious way
of being that our brain evolved

00:44:39.320 --> 00:44:41.940
to have, OK?

00:44:41.940 --> 00:44:46.110
And if we add intention
to play, we get science.

00:44:46.110 --> 00:44:49.650
Science is nothing other
than play with intention.

00:44:49.650 --> 00:44:52.920
Empiricism is
inherent to the brain.

00:44:52.920 --> 00:44:55.730
And how do you define science,
and how do you define play?

00:44:55.730 --> 00:44:56.940
So it's not like play.

00:44:56.940 --> 00:44:59.090
It literally is play.

00:44:59.090 --> 00:45:01.490
When we created an education
program based on this,

00:45:01.490 --> 00:45:03.489
it resulted in the youngest
published scientists

00:45:03.489 --> 00:45:05.230
in the world, aged
eight to 10 years old,

00:45:05.230 --> 00:45:08.080
and the youngest
ever TED speaker.

00:45:08.080 --> 00:45:10.420
Because if you add rules
to play, you have a game.

00:45:10.420 --> 00:45:12.630
That's an experiment.

00:45:12.630 --> 00:45:15.987
But it's rethinking what science
is, which is not a methodology.

00:45:15.987 --> 00:45:17.820
That is the craft of
science, but that's not

00:45:17.820 --> 00:45:19.350
what defines science.

00:45:19.350 --> 00:45:22.990
Science is this way of being,
which celebrates uncertainty.

00:45:22.990 --> 00:45:24.780
It encourages diversity.

00:45:24.780 --> 00:45:26.430
It's actually how
we create diversity.

00:45:26.430 --> 00:45:29.670
The function of science is, in
fact, to increase uncertainty.

00:45:29.670 --> 00:45:33.879
Because quality of science
isn't the question you ask.

00:45:33.879 --> 00:45:34.920
It's open to possibility.

00:45:34.920 --> 00:45:38.440
It's inherently cooperative and
it's intrinsically motivating.

00:45:38.440 --> 00:45:40.440
What does it mean to be
intrinsically motivated?

00:45:40.440 --> 00:45:42.606
Almost everything you do,
you do for a reward that's

00:45:42.606 --> 00:45:44.430
different from what you do.

00:45:44.430 --> 00:45:48.330
What is the reward for skiing?

00:45:48.330 --> 00:45:49.660
It's skiing.

00:45:49.660 --> 00:45:52.610
The reward for play
is play itself.

00:45:52.610 --> 00:45:54.440
It's intrinsically motivating.

00:45:54.440 --> 00:45:55.850
And that's true
for anything that

00:45:55.850 --> 00:45:58.100
is in the process of discovery.

00:45:58.100 --> 00:46:00.770
The reward of science,
the reward of discovery

00:46:00.770 --> 00:46:03.170
is the discovery itself.

00:46:03.170 --> 00:46:06.530
And these are actually
what defines play.

00:46:06.530 --> 00:46:09.795
And if we add intention
to play, you have science.

00:46:09.795 --> 00:46:11.280
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:46:20.200 --> 00:46:21.260
BEAU LOTTO: That's true.

00:46:21.260 --> 00:46:22.600
So I'm not talking about
the output of science.

00:46:22.600 --> 00:46:24.580
But I wouldn't say
science is about truth.

00:46:24.580 --> 00:46:26.680
Science is about utility.

00:46:26.680 --> 00:46:28.420
Evolution is not about truth.

00:46:28.420 --> 00:46:31.910
Evolution is about what's
useful, about predictable,

00:46:31.910 --> 00:46:32.410
right?

00:46:32.410 --> 00:46:34.734
Even with our mathematics,
we have theorems.

00:46:34.734 --> 00:46:36.400
All that theorems are
is making explicit

00:46:36.400 --> 00:46:37.483
what your assumptions are.

00:46:37.483 --> 00:46:39.040
Given these set of
assumptions, this

00:46:39.040 --> 00:46:40.720
is what we believe to be true.

00:46:40.720 --> 00:46:45.100
True is that this is far more
predictable than that was.

00:46:45.100 --> 00:46:47.710
So my theory of neuroscience,
for instance, so I'm

00:46:47.710 --> 00:46:51.070
looking at neurotropic factors
in brain cell growth, right?

00:46:51.070 --> 00:46:52.870
I'm looking empirically
to see, what

00:46:52.870 --> 00:46:55.750
is the most likely explanation
for the data that I've got?

00:46:55.750 --> 00:46:57.970
I'm looking for
understanding that

00:46:57.970 --> 00:47:00.400
decreases dimensionality
of the space of possibility

00:47:00.400 --> 00:47:02.970
of the search, right?

00:47:02.970 --> 00:47:06.540
So if I can reduce it to
one variable versus two,

00:47:06.540 --> 00:47:09.620
I have a better explanation.

00:47:09.620 --> 00:47:10.550
That's utility.

00:47:10.550 --> 00:47:11.660
That's useful.

00:47:11.660 --> 00:47:13.130
I'm making a prediction.

00:47:13.130 --> 00:47:13.910
Is it true?

00:47:13.910 --> 00:47:17.860
Well, then we get into the
semantics of what true is.

00:47:17.860 --> 00:47:20.190
And you could argue,
that is truth.

00:47:20.190 --> 00:47:22.800
To be able to predict in
every single situation

00:47:22.800 --> 00:47:25.340
is potentially true, right?

00:47:25.340 --> 00:47:28.100
But in terms of, for instance,
what your brain is doing,

00:47:28.100 --> 00:47:29.960
if your brain is
when the cricket

00:47:29.960 --> 00:47:34.640
or when the male fly is trying
to mate with the female fly,

00:47:34.640 --> 00:47:37.010
and it's trying to
predict her trajectory,

00:47:37.010 --> 00:47:39.156
we can mathematically
model that.

00:47:39.156 --> 00:47:41.030
Is that mathematical
model actually happening

00:47:41.030 --> 00:47:41.810
inside that brain?

00:47:41.810 --> 00:47:43.580
No.

00:47:43.580 --> 00:47:48.080
It's generated behavior
that is useful, right?

00:47:48.080 --> 00:47:49.460
Empirically.

00:47:49.460 --> 00:47:53.940
Over the course of evolution,
learning, and development.

00:47:53.940 --> 00:47:55.610
So science is about absolutely--

00:47:55.610 --> 00:47:57.819
I'm not saying this is
post-modern relativism at all.

00:47:57.819 --> 00:47:59.360
Post-modern relativism
doesn't exist.

00:47:59.360 --> 00:48:01.100
If it did, evolution
wouldn't exist.

00:48:01.100 --> 00:48:03.145
Some things are
better than others.

00:48:03.145 --> 00:48:05.270
We just don't know what
they are a priori, which is

00:48:05.270 --> 00:48:07.750
why we have empiricism, right?

00:48:07.750 --> 00:48:10.840
What we get from that
is truth in the sense

00:48:10.840 --> 00:48:12.760
that it's highly
predictable or more

00:48:12.760 --> 00:48:15.880
predictable than
the previous theory.

00:48:15.880 --> 00:48:17.140
OK?

00:48:17.140 --> 00:48:20.020
And the way we do that-- but
that's the process of science.

00:48:20.020 --> 00:48:22.250
That's the scientific method.

00:48:22.250 --> 00:48:23.930
But in order to
do that, you have

00:48:23.930 --> 00:48:26.380
to be able to ask
a good question.

00:48:26.380 --> 00:48:28.090
And in order to
ask that question,

00:48:28.090 --> 00:48:31.260
you have to celebrate the
possibility of being wrong,

00:48:31.260 --> 00:48:33.910
of not knowing, right?

00:48:33.910 --> 00:48:36.040
So my suggestion is
that what underpins

00:48:36.040 --> 00:48:40.280
good science is a way of being
that we actually call play.

00:48:40.280 --> 00:48:41.830
And it underpins
not just science.

00:48:41.830 --> 00:48:43.660
Anything that is creative.

00:48:43.660 --> 00:48:45.560
Whereas play has no intention.

00:48:45.560 --> 00:48:47.350
It's just simply
for the sake of it.

00:48:47.350 --> 00:48:50.630
Something like science or art
actually has an intention.

00:48:50.630 --> 00:48:53.160
It's trying to do something.

00:48:53.160 --> 00:48:55.090
See what I mean?

00:48:55.090 --> 00:48:58.135
AUDIENCE: Earlier, you had a
video of people arguing about,

00:48:58.135 --> 00:48:59.830
where was Barack Obama born?

00:48:59.830 --> 00:49:01.797
And the way you've
defined science,

00:49:01.797 --> 00:49:03.880
I would interpret that to
mean it doesn't actually

00:49:03.880 --> 00:49:06.130
matter where he was born,
that where he was born

00:49:06.130 --> 00:49:07.720
doesn't have an answer.

00:49:07.720 --> 00:49:10.220
The only thing that matters
is what your bias is

00:49:10.220 --> 00:49:12.730
or whether it fits your
subset of evidence.

00:49:12.730 --> 00:49:15.880
The question of where
he was really born

00:49:15.880 --> 00:49:18.700
doesn't really exist
anywhere in this definition,

00:49:18.700 --> 00:49:21.130
and that's the reason why
I don't buy the definition.

00:49:21.130 --> 00:49:24.370
That question has an answer, and
that answer is external to me,

00:49:24.370 --> 00:49:26.440
and it's external to my biases.

00:49:26.440 --> 00:49:29.080
And it may be true that
I have this or that bias,

00:49:29.080 --> 00:49:33.400
but my biases have
only a limited power.

00:49:33.400 --> 00:49:38.200
My biases do not change
where Barack Obama was born.

00:49:38.200 --> 00:49:40.480
That fact is completely
independent of my biases.

00:49:40.480 --> 00:49:44.650
And so I find this definition
of science to be incomplete,

00:49:44.650 --> 00:49:47.772
because science absolutely
does care about reality.

00:49:47.772 --> 00:49:48.480
BEAU LOTTO: Yeah.

00:49:48.480 --> 00:49:52.060
I completely-- it doesn't
necessarily care about reality.

00:49:52.060 --> 00:49:54.640
It cares about predictability.

00:49:54.640 --> 00:49:57.340
The two can be very
coincident, yeah?

00:49:57.340 --> 00:49:59.815
So I completely--
the process-- the aim

00:49:59.815 --> 00:50:01.690
here is not to define
the process of science,

00:50:01.690 --> 00:50:04.930
the scientific method, which of
course, I apply in my own lab.

00:50:04.930 --> 00:50:07.581
What I'm trying to
suggest is that in order

00:50:07.581 --> 00:50:09.580
to apply that method, you
need to have something

00:50:09.580 --> 00:50:12.140
that comes first, right?

00:50:12.140 --> 00:50:14.904
You have to have a
desire to ask a question.

00:50:14.904 --> 00:50:16.820
You have to have the
willingness to doubt what

00:50:16.820 --> 00:50:17.930
you think to be true already.

00:50:17.930 --> 00:50:20.570
You have to be willing to doubt
your own biases to think, well,

00:50:20.570 --> 00:50:24.440
maybe Barack Obama was
actually born here.

00:50:24.440 --> 00:50:27.020
You have to have that if you're
going to do good science,

00:50:27.020 --> 00:50:29.840
ie, if you're going to apply
a good scientific method.

00:50:29.840 --> 00:50:32.520
But you could have designed
the greatest experiment,

00:50:32.520 --> 00:50:36.170
but if you have a crap
question, who cares, right?

00:50:36.170 --> 00:50:39.200
Because then you find
a useless answer.

00:50:39.200 --> 00:50:41.550
I want you to come up
with a great answer,

00:50:41.550 --> 00:50:44.370
but to do that, you have
to ask a great question.

00:50:44.370 --> 00:50:46.170
I want you to be a
great experimentalist,

00:50:46.170 --> 00:50:47.920
but you could be the
best experimentalist,

00:50:47.920 --> 00:50:50.950
but you'll still be
a crap scientist.

00:50:50.950 --> 00:50:52.480
Because you'll come
up with useless

00:50:52.480 --> 00:50:55.240
answers if you're
not willing to ask

00:50:55.240 --> 00:50:57.430
a question, especially a
question that challenges

00:50:57.430 --> 00:50:58.840
your own assumptions.

00:50:58.840 --> 00:51:00.344
And that's what
science is, is to be

00:51:00.344 --> 00:51:02.260
able to challenge your
own assumptions of what

00:51:02.260 --> 00:51:04.060
you think is true.

00:51:04.060 --> 00:51:06.700
But to do that, your brain
evolved to take you away

00:51:06.700 --> 00:51:08.380
from that place.

00:51:08.380 --> 00:51:11.065
And one of the only places
literally in evolution

00:51:11.065 --> 00:51:13.660
that it enables you to
challenge your own biases

00:51:13.660 --> 00:51:15.960
is in the context of play.

00:51:15.960 --> 00:51:18.400
That's the way of being
that enables you to do that.

00:51:18.400 --> 00:51:20.340
And then you apply
the scientific method

00:51:20.340 --> 00:51:22.170
of empiricism, right?

00:51:22.170 --> 00:51:24.540
One control, one
variable, et cetera.

00:51:24.540 --> 00:51:27.480
But having one control is like
defining an artist's painting

00:51:27.480 --> 00:51:31.650
based on the brushstrokes
or the pigment chemistry.

00:51:31.650 --> 00:51:34.590
The mechanism of painting is
not what defines whether or not

00:51:34.590 --> 00:51:36.840
it was a good piece of art.

00:51:36.840 --> 00:51:38.185
It's the view.

00:51:38.185 --> 00:51:40.060
This is incomplete in
the sense that you then

00:51:40.060 --> 00:51:42.870
apply a scientific method
on top of it, absolutely.

00:51:42.870 --> 00:51:45.370
And the intention of science
is different from the intention

00:51:45.370 --> 00:51:46.660
of art.

00:51:46.660 --> 00:51:49.964
But the initiation, the desire
to go forward is the same,

00:51:49.964 --> 00:51:50.630
is the argument.

00:51:50.630 --> 00:51:51.730
