is actually dark--

00:54:22.190 --> 00:54:25.190
is the same intensity
as the see there.

00:54:25.190 --> 00:54:26.949
Right now you're
seeing an illusion.

00:54:26.949 --> 00:54:29.240
But as soon as you know that
you're seeing an illusion,

00:54:29.240 --> 00:54:31.490
your brain is holding two
mutually exclusive realities

00:54:31.490 --> 00:54:33.500
at the same time, you're
seeing one reality,

00:54:33.500 --> 00:54:36.080
but you also know
another reality.

00:54:36.080 --> 00:54:38.390
That's an incredibly powerful
thing for our brains,

00:54:38.390 --> 00:54:40.640
to be able to hold two
mutually exclusive ideas

00:54:40.640 --> 00:54:42.020
at the same time.

00:54:42.020 --> 00:54:44.320
That is the basis
for imagination.

00:54:44.320 --> 00:54:45.940
OK?

00:54:45.940 --> 00:54:50.600
So this relates
ultimately to conflict.

00:54:50.600 --> 00:54:54.549
If conflict is the only place
where we can actually learn--

00:54:54.549 --> 00:54:56.090
and by definition
of conflict, I mean

00:54:56.090 --> 00:54:58.548
to enter a situation that is
different from what you assume

00:54:58.548 --> 00:54:59.990
to be true, you're in conflict.

00:54:59.990 --> 00:55:02.360
Evolution, in that sense,
you could argue conceptually

00:55:02.360 --> 00:55:03.770
as a conflicting process.

00:55:03.770 --> 00:55:06.680
That's the only place where
we can actually change.

00:55:06.680 --> 00:55:09.830
The problem is we enter conflict
in usually the same way.

00:55:09.830 --> 00:55:11.720
If you and I are
in disagreement,

00:55:11.720 --> 00:55:14.120
it's as if we're on different
ends of the same line.

00:55:14.120 --> 00:55:15.710
My aim is to prove
that you're wrong

00:55:15.710 --> 00:55:17.418
and to shift you
towards me, and your aim

00:55:17.418 --> 00:55:19.390
is to do exactly the opposite.

00:55:19.390 --> 00:55:22.730
In that format of conflict,
we're set up to win,

00:55:22.730 --> 00:55:25.560
but not necessarily learn.

00:55:25.560 --> 00:55:29.404
The question is, how does
biology deal with conflict?

00:55:29.404 --> 00:55:30.070
Here's a riddle.

00:55:30.070 --> 00:55:33.152
How can you move those
two dots closer together

00:55:33.152 --> 00:55:35.568
without actually shifting the
location of the dots at all?

00:55:41.046 --> 00:55:42.690
AUDIENCE: Enlarge the circles.

00:55:42.690 --> 00:55:45.300
BEAU LOTTO: Enlarge
the circles, right?

00:55:45.300 --> 00:55:47.180
You increase the space.

00:55:47.180 --> 00:55:50.280
You increase the dimensionality
of the space, right?

00:55:50.280 --> 00:55:52.830
In the case of genetics, it's
called extradimensional bypass,

00:55:52.830 --> 00:55:53.329
right?

00:55:53.329 --> 00:55:55.780
You complexify.

00:55:55.780 --> 00:55:57.507
You complexify the system.

00:55:57.507 --> 00:55:59.840
So while we might be at
opposite ends of the same lines,

00:55:59.840 --> 00:56:02.740
we can actually be at
same side of a square.

00:56:02.740 --> 00:56:06.037
It now gives you more
directions in which to move.

00:56:06.037 --> 00:56:07.870
As you increase the
dimensionality of space,

00:56:07.870 --> 00:56:10.970
you actually relatively become
closer and closer together,

00:56:10.970 --> 00:56:11.470
right?

00:56:11.470 --> 00:56:13.720
Now you create the possibility
of learning rather than

00:56:13.720 --> 00:56:14.754
just winning.

00:56:14.754 --> 00:56:16.420
And this is how
actually nature resolves

00:56:16.420 --> 00:56:21.809
conflict, by increasing the
dimensionality of space.

00:56:21.809 --> 00:56:23.100
So we'll finish with that idea.

00:56:23.100 --> 00:56:24.974
So imagine, in order to
do that, you actually

00:56:24.974 --> 00:56:28.630
have to enter conflict with a
question instead of an answer.

00:56:28.630 --> 00:56:30.220
And that's the
space-- that's the way

00:56:30.220 --> 00:56:32.690
of being that's required in
order to do good science.

00:56:32.690 --> 00:56:36.702
You enter with a question
rather than with an answer.

00:56:36.702 --> 00:56:37.690
OK?

00:56:37.690 --> 00:56:39.840
So I hope that's useful.

00:56:39.840 --> 00:56:41.170
OK?

00:56:41.170 --> 00:56:42.540
So any questions?

00:56:47.599 --> 00:56:48.140
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:56:48.140 --> 00:56:50.450
This feels weird
talking on this.

00:56:50.450 --> 00:56:52.520
I've read an article
from a mathematician that

00:56:52.520 --> 00:56:53.984
ends up questioning reality.

00:56:53.984 --> 00:56:56.150
And he says-- the biggest
thing that stuck out to me

00:56:56.150 --> 00:57:00.570
was, neuroscientists are
asking the wrong question.

00:57:00.570 --> 00:57:02.320
They shouldn't be
asking what's happening.

00:57:02.320 --> 00:57:05.570
They should be asking, does
the gray matter even exist?

00:57:05.570 --> 00:57:08.630
If we're always constantly
perceiving things incorrectly,

00:57:08.630 --> 00:57:12.680
or shared perception is kind
of off, does the brain exist?

00:57:12.680 --> 00:57:14.990
Does this chair even
exist in this reality,

00:57:14.990 --> 00:57:16.040
or are we sharing that?

00:57:16.040 --> 00:57:18.260
And I don't-- I'd like to hear
from a neuroscientist to tell

00:57:18.260 --> 00:57:18.950
me a little bit about it.

00:57:18.950 --> 00:57:19.658
BEAU LOTTO: Yeah.

00:57:19.658 --> 00:57:21.380
So the world exists.

00:57:21.380 --> 00:57:23.780
The physical world
exists, right?

00:57:23.780 --> 00:57:26.140
What we perceive of that
world is not the same thing

00:57:26.140 --> 00:57:27.980
as the world itself.

00:57:27.980 --> 00:57:29.960
I'll give you a
very simple example

00:57:29.960 --> 00:57:32.600
to demonstrate that
this has to be true.

00:57:32.600 --> 00:57:33.750
Take light.

00:57:33.750 --> 00:57:36.110
Light is a linear
spectrum from--

00:57:36.110 --> 00:57:38.610
well, actually, it's
electromagnetic radiation,

00:57:38.610 --> 00:57:40.010
which is a huge spectrum.

00:57:40.010 --> 00:57:43.310
We are sensitive to a very small
window, which by definition, we

00:57:43.310 --> 00:57:44.310
call light.

00:57:44.310 --> 00:57:46.950
Light is part of the region
that we're sensitive to.

00:57:46.950 --> 00:57:48.010
[INAUDIBLE]

00:57:48.010 --> 00:57:50.810
It's a linear spectrum, right?

00:57:50.810 --> 00:57:53.540
We perceive that as a circle.

00:57:53.540 --> 00:57:55.310
We perceive the
short wavelengths

00:57:55.310 --> 00:57:58.880
to be blue and the long
wavelengths to be red.

00:57:58.880 --> 00:58:00.590
Which means that
perceptually, they

00:58:00.590 --> 00:58:02.390
appear more similar
to each other

00:58:02.390 --> 00:58:04.340
than they do to green,
which is in the middle.

00:58:04.340 --> 00:58:06.629
Even though they're
physically closer to green,

00:58:06.629 --> 00:58:08.670
they are perceptually more
similar to each other.

00:58:08.670 --> 00:58:12.530
It's a bit like one kilo
feeling a lot like 1,000 kilos,

00:58:12.530 --> 00:58:15.050
but very different
from 500 kilos.

00:58:15.050 --> 00:58:17.570
So even there in our
perception of color,

00:58:17.570 --> 00:58:22.100
we don't do an isomorphic
representation of light itself.

00:58:22.100 --> 00:58:23.990
Our perception of
light is also color.

00:58:23.990 --> 00:58:27.740
It has four categories, red,
green, blue, and yellow.

00:58:27.740 --> 00:58:31.700
Spectra are uniformly,
continuously changing.

00:58:31.700 --> 00:58:34.430
There's nothing
categorical about light.

00:58:34.430 --> 00:58:36.410
And yet, it was
perceptually useful to see

00:58:36.410 --> 00:58:38.652
light in terms of
four categories,

00:58:38.652 --> 00:58:40.610
possibly because of the
four-color map problem,

00:58:40.610 --> 00:58:43.700
cartography, where you need
four colors, a minimum of four

00:58:43.700 --> 00:58:46.790
colors to color any map in
order to make sure two surfaces

00:58:46.790 --> 00:58:48.800
don't actually have
the same color, two

00:58:48.800 --> 00:58:50.336
adjoining surfaces [INAUDIBLE].

00:58:50.336 --> 00:58:51.710
So it could be
useful that that's

00:58:51.710 --> 00:58:53.690
why we see four
categories of color.

00:58:53.690 --> 00:58:59.102
But it has nothing to do with
the category nature of spectra.

00:58:59.102 --> 00:59:00.710
So spectra exists.

00:59:00.710 --> 00:59:03.890
It's just that we don't
represent them as spectra.

00:59:03.890 --> 00:59:05.990
We represent them in a
way that was useful, not

00:59:05.990 --> 00:59:07.906
in the way that was accurate.

00:59:07.906 --> 00:59:08.406
Yeah?

00:59:14.310 --> 00:59:16.510
AUDIENCE: I was just
wondering whether it

00:59:16.510 --> 00:59:20.470
has to do with genetics
about how people stress out

00:59:20.470 --> 00:59:21.800
about uncertainty.

00:59:21.800 --> 00:59:25.900
So I don't get nauseous on
the boats, and some people do.

00:59:25.900 --> 00:59:27.850
The question is, does
it imply that I'm

00:59:27.850 --> 00:59:30.400
more tolerant to
uncertainty, and hence,

00:59:30.400 --> 00:59:34.320
better at doing open
questions and doing science

00:59:34.320 --> 00:59:35.910
than these other people?

00:59:35.910 --> 00:59:36.670
BEAU LOTTO: Yeah.

00:59:36.670 --> 00:59:38.000
So it's a very good question.

00:59:38.000 --> 00:59:40.240
I think it is true that
some people actually

00:59:40.240 --> 00:59:43.280
have more tolerance for
uncertainty than others.

00:59:43.280 --> 00:59:46.220
And it's also a really important
question why they might be so.

00:59:46.220 --> 00:59:47.680
Now it could be genetic.

00:59:47.680 --> 00:59:51.040
But also, if you think
about parenting--

00:59:51.040 --> 00:59:53.240
so I have three kids.

00:59:53.240 --> 00:59:55.400
My role, in some
sense, is to create

00:59:55.400 --> 00:59:58.402
the certainty that enables
them to step into uncertainty.

00:59:58.402 --> 01:00:00.610
Because you can't step into
uncertainty unless you're

01:00:00.610 --> 01:00:03.220
stepping from someplace.

01:00:03.220 --> 01:00:06.040
You can't play outside
of space that's trusted.

01:00:06.040 --> 01:00:08.610
So people who often can
tolerate uncertainty,

01:00:08.610 --> 01:00:10.540
it's because they have
something very certain

01:00:10.540 --> 01:00:11.539
that counterbalances it.

01:00:13.879 --> 01:00:15.920
And so a lot of education,
a lot of [INAUDIBLE],,

01:00:15.920 --> 01:00:18.796
is about trying to create
that certainty, right?

01:00:18.796 --> 01:00:20.420
It could be through
love, for instance,

01:00:20.420 --> 01:00:21.920
that enables a
child, in this case,

01:00:21.920 --> 01:00:24.020
to feel very
wanted, that enables

01:00:24.020 --> 01:00:28.220
them to now step into and
be courageous and explore.

01:00:28.220 --> 01:00:29.840
But often, kids
that don't have that

01:00:29.840 --> 01:00:32.180
find it very difficult
to be in uncertainty,

01:00:32.180 --> 01:00:35.030
because so much of
their life is uncertain.

01:00:35.030 --> 01:00:39.100
They're actually looking for
certainly, not uncertainty.

01:00:39.100 --> 01:00:40.470
So I don't know if it's genetic.

01:00:40.470 --> 01:00:42.750
There seems to possibly
be a genetic component.

01:00:42.750 --> 01:00:46.470
But there definitely is a
difference in people, right?

01:00:46.470 --> 01:00:48.840
But the idea here is that we
can actually help people--

01:00:48.840 --> 01:00:50.627
other people step
into uncertainty

01:00:50.627 --> 01:00:53.085
by helping to create an ecology
that enables them to do so.

